The mega-model is primarily concerned with expressing relationships between systems.

A language is a set of systems.

attributes.documentation:
The mission goals specify the target parameters across the system.
The difficulty with mission goals is that they can be specific or general.
In this sample model they tend toward the more specific.
They define a few types of messages and the rates that those messages are sent/received from/by specific devices.

attributes.documentation:
#### Representation-of (represents)

 * src : model
 * dst : system-under-study (SUS)

If the model is derived from the SUS then it is a 'descriptive-model'.
If the SUS is constructed from the model, as from a blueprint, then it is a 'specification-model'.

#### Composes (decomposition)

 * src : whole composite
 * dst : part component


#### Element-of (membership)
 
 * src : element
 * dst : set

#### Conforms-to (meta-models)

 * src : conformant model
 * dst : meta-model

Conformance of a model to a meta-model is equivalent to a mega-pattern involving a chain from 
'meta-model' which represents a 'modeling language' a member of which is a 'conformant model'.
There is a presumption that this 'conformant model' represents some domain specific 'system-under-study'.
The stereotypical devices {A, B, C} represented here are replicated in the location model.

The Actual-Network should mirror the Specified-Network augmenting it with Measured-Values.
The workflow identifies the difference between the network models and generates tasks 
intended to bring them into conformance (or at least compliance).
This is the server that provides the situational awareness gateway.

attributes.documentation:
### Mission Goals : Challenge Problem #1

#### Qualitative Goals

Location-data are generated by gps-devices.
This location-data can be saasm {required, optional, ?} as a goal.
The location-data goal can be set for the mission or by device.
(This is achieved by setting setting the saasm setting on the base mobile-device or on specific devices.)

These location-data are used to compose location-messages by mobile-devices.
The mobile-devices send the location-messages to the sa-server.
The sa-server distributes the location-messages to all mobile-devices.

This simple model reflects the essential elements of a set of Android devices communicating with a central server.

There are three variations on the nexus-7 device configuration A, B, and C.
The instances for these three types are either created here {A1:A5, C1} or in the deployment model {B1:B4}.

attributes.documentation:
#### Challenge Problem #2


The second challenge problem gets tricker. There are more Control
Points, and we haven't settled yet on all the possible DFU
implementations. This is a super-set of the first challenge problem, so
we have all those plus we're looking at things like:

  * X-compatibility: compatibility with external system X might force us
to use a particular wire-protocol for SA messages or images, where 'X'
is outside the scope of the software system we are able to modify. This
might force us to use a wire-protocol that is less efficient in terms of
bandwidth.
  * most-constrained link bandwidth: this will be consumed according to
the rate of sending SA and images from each clients, and the number of
clients
  * image properties (color vs. b&w, resolution, etc)

In UML2 this is called 'Device'.
This is the hardware which provides an ExecutionPlatform.
There will be certain types of ExecutionEnvironments which may be installed on this device.
In order to clarify the role but preserve the name from UML this will be called ExecutionDevice.
Language
attributes.name: Doc: Language

attributes.documentation:
#### Challenge Problem #1

For the first Challenge Problem we've only got the client to worry
about, and only one Control point, which is of type "LocationProvider".
The DFU implementations of "LocationProvider" that we're considering
initially have the following resource requirements:

 * Internal GPS: requires
    * GPS-chipset on device
    * GPS satellite availability
 * External GPS; requires
    * connectivity method (USB or bluetooth)
    * GPS satellite availability
 * SAASM GPS: instance of External GPS, so has those req's plus:
    * connectivity must be USB
    * SAASM Crypto key
 * Dead reckoning; requires
    * User interface + map display

Those are the pre-requisites in terms of "external resources" for each
DFU. (by 'external' I mean they will be given as part of the environment
description; for example: we will never be able to make a bluetooth
connection if the hardware doesn't exist on the target device).  We
might end up with a few layers of indirection (e.g. the DFU depends on a
bluetooth library, and the bluetooth library has a dependency on the
bluetooth chipset/hardware), but for these purposes I tried to make the
shortest-path possible to hardware/external dependencies.

### Deployment, Network & Mission Sample
This project develops a schema for deployment to client/server, android/java.
This is a 2-model consisting of a deployment model and a network model.
These models must also reflect the design intent as well as multiple realizations.

#### Network Stereotypes

The Network Stereotypes reflect those items that are needed to express the 
network connectivity and the channels they represent.
These channels have several capacities including expected and actual.
In addition a channel may not be possible (or simply not selected in the implementation).

#### Deployment Stereotypes

The Deployment Stereotypes roughly reflect the UML2 deployment diagram language.
